
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `bzip2recover` baraye peyda kardane block-haye data zarar dide az file-haye `.bz2` va bazsazi (recover) onha be tore joda estefade mishavad. In dastoor vaghti karbord dare ke yek file `bzip2` az beyn rafte ya kamelan ghabele khandan nist.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 hich gozine-ye khas nadare. Dastoor sade ast.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ bzip2recover filename.bz2

    🔹 Dastoor file ra scan mikonad va block-haye bazsazi shode ra dar file-haye jadid zakhire mikonad.

    $ ls rec*.bz2

    🔹 Namayesh file-haye bazsazi shode (rec0001.bz2, rec0002.bz2, ...)

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ bzip2recover data.bz2
    rec0001.bz2 sakhte shod.
    rec0002.bz2 sakhte shod.

    🔹 In neshan midahad ke dastoor do blocke data bazsazi shode ra peyda karde va anha ra be عنوان do file-ye joda zakhire karde ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `bzip2recover` command is used to find individual damaged data blocks from `.bz2` files and recover them independently. This is useful when a `bzip2` file is corrupted or not fully readable.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 It does not have any specific options. The command is straightforward.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ bzip2recover filename.bz2

    🔹 The command scans the file and saves recovered blocks into new files.

    $ ls rec*.bz2

    🔹 Shows the recovered files (rec0001.bz2, rec0002.bz2, ...).

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ bzip2recover data.bz2
    rec0001.bz2 created.
    rec0002.bz2 created.

    🔹 This indicates that the command found and recovered two data blocks, saving them as two separate files.
